The paper introduces a novel auto-encoder architecture for dictionary learning and blind source separation, which involves optimization-based alternating-minimization schemes and sparse coding. These techniques are commonly used in machine learning and computer vision, suggesting that the paper may belong to the cs.LG and cs.CV sub-categories. Additionally, the paper applies the proposed method to spike sorting, a problem in computational neuroscience, which could place it in the cs.NE sub-category. The paper also discusses the sensitivity of the method to signal-to-noise ratio, which could suggest a connection to the cs.SD sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of constraints in the encoder and decoder, which could relate to the cs.AI sub-category.
